On to the Update:

Microsoft Earnings
------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/business/earnings/micros=
oft-msft-q4-earnings-report-2024-0f766bfe ) :

Microsoft reported growth in its main cloud-computing business that narrowl=
y missed expectations, causing its stock to drop during after-hours trading=
 in the midst of investor jitters over the outlook for the artificial-intel=
ligence boom. The tech giant=E2=80=99s overall sales and profit growth beat=
 expectations in the latest quarter. But revenue for its Azure cloud busine=
ss=E2=80=94a central part of its AI operation=E2=80=94rose 29%. That was be=
low the prior quarter=E2=80=99s 31% growth and lagged behind analysts=E2=80=
=99 expectations it would rise by 30%, according to FactSet.

Microsoft=E2=80=99s stock was down 2.8% in after-hours trading, a sign of h=
ow sensitive traders are to the slightest sign of weakness in the company=
=E2=80=99s all-important cloud business, which is at the heart of Chief Exe=
cutive Satya Nadella=E2=80=99s artificial-intelligence strategy.

The interesting thing about investor skittishness about Microsoft=E2=80=99s=
 results is that the AI-related portions seemed mostly positive; CFO Amy Ho=
od said in her prepared remarks on the earnings call ( https://seekingalpha=
.com/article/4708295-microsoft-corporation-msft-q4-2024-earnings-call-trans=
cript ) :

Next, the Intelligent Cloud segment. Revenue was $28.5 billion, increasing =
19% and 20% in constant currency, in line with expectations. Overall, serve=
r products and cloud services revenue grew 21% and 22% in constant currency=
. Azure and other cloud services revenue grew 29% and 30% in constant curre=
ncy, in line with expectations and consistent with Q3 when adjusting for le=
ap year. Azure growth included 8 points from AI services where demand remai=
ned higher than our available capacity. In June, we saw slightly lower-than=
-expected growth in a few European geos.

In the question-and-answer section Hood emphasized that the European miss w=
as not related to AI:

Maybe I=E2=80=99ll just repeat it, just so people can hear it in my words a=
s well to that 30% to 31% guide for Q4 and coming in at the lower end of 30=
%. You=E2=80=99re exactly right. The distinguishing between being at the hi=
gher end or at the lower end, really was some softness we saw in a few Euro=
pean geos on non-AI consumption really made the difference in that number. =
And we=E2=80=99ve assumed that going forward into H1 inclusive of my guide =
28% to 29% going forward. And then let me separate which was your larger po=
int, which is what are the other factors you see ongoing. Number one, you=
=E2=80=99re right, capacity constraints, particularly on AI and Azure will =
remain in Q4 and will remain in H1. So hopefully, that=E2=80=99s helpful.

The eight points in AI-related growth is higher than last quarter=E2=80=99s=
 seven points, and it seems like a good sign for capex concerns that growth=
 was capacity constrained. Of course that shortage in capacity is downstrea=
m of capital expenditure decisions made a long time ago; the big question i=
s if all of the spending happening now will provide a return down the road.

CoPilot and CapEx
-----------------

To that end, CEO Satya Nadella spent a lot of time on the call re-assuring =
investors that Microsoft had the ability to gate its capital expenditures; =
most of his arguments were captured in this answer to an analyst question, =
which I will address piece-by-piece:

Let me start, and then Amy can add to this. I think, I would say we primari=
ly start right now from the demand side. What I mean by that is what=E2=80=
=99s the product =E2=80=93 shape of the product portfolio, what we learned =
even from the cloud transition, which, as you know, Keith, was similar in t=
he sense it was both a knowledge-intensive and a capital-intensive transiti=
on. We needed to have the product portfolio where there was the right mix o=
f, I=E2=80=99ll call it, infrastructure meters as well as SaaS applications=
. So that=E2=80=99s the first thing that we are looking at, and how is that=
 value landing with customers and what=E2=80=99s the growth rate. So when I=
 think about what=E2=80=99s happening with M365 Copilot as perhaps the best=
 Office 365 or M365 suite we have had, the fact that we=E2=80=99re getting =
recurring customers, so our customers coming back buying more seats. So Git=
Hub Copilot now being bigger than even GitHub when we bought it.

Nadella=E2=80=99s argument is that Microsoft isn=E2=80=99t just building ge=
neric AI infrastructure, but actually building AI products; this means that=
 Microsoft can both drive demand based on its ability to deliver those prod=
ucts, and, by extension, has good visibility into demand because it can see=
 how well those products are selling. To that end, Nadella threw out a bunc=
h of numbers with regards to AI Copilot adoption, but nothing concrete; the=
 best thing Microsoft could do to allay investor concerns is to drop a mean=
ingful dollar figure in terms of AI Copilot revenue contributions.

What is notable is GitHub CoPilot traction; from Nadella=E2=80=99s prepared=
 remarks:

GitHub Copilot is by far the most widely adopted AI-powered developer tool.=
 Just over two years since its general availability, more than 77,000 organ=
izations from BBVA, FedEx, and H&M, to Infosys and Paytm have adopted Copil=
ot, up 180% year-over-year. And we are going further. With Copilot Workspac=
e, we offer Copilot-native end-to-end developer productivity across plan, b=
uild, test, debug, and deploy cycle. Copilot is driving GitHub growth, all =
up, GitHub=E2=80=99s annual revenue run rate is now $2 billion. Copilot acc=
ounted for over 40% of GitHub revenue growth this year, and is already a la=
rger business than all of GitHub was when we acquired it.

I was very much in favor of the GitHub acquisition, which happened in 2018 =
for =E2=80=9Conly=E2=80=9D $7.5 billion, but my expectations were modest: I=
 wrote in an Update at the time ( https://stratechery.com/2018/microsoft-to=
-buy-github-a-win-for-github-facebooks-data-sharing-deals-with-device-maker=
s/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0L=
m9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmU=
iLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3=
N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE4L21pY3Jvc29mdC10by1idXktZ2l0aHViLWEtd2luLWZvci1na=
XRodWItZmFjZWJvb2tzLWRhdGEtc2hhcmluZy1kZWFscy13aXRoLWRldmljZS1tYWtlcnMvIl19=
LCJleHAiOjE3MjUwMzAwMjAsImlhdCI6MTcyMjQzODAyMCwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGF=
zc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2=
V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV=
0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.ICQWNA8RjOfoMlcfEcGtRhJY8HzhOoppmliDQxoW=
BeWbFJU6w-fqBQ115fMECFZuaI11IsKfx4RefmR3NojXIBxqythXbxy3sv68M1nN8hM211fHEm8=
ZyL3WsS18vUZ8GzDR3jc2deCmZXYILh7qyPIcUyRAZKgvDvvWTPm3ksN7fw2kBGEfUyohOniWzz=
q9yZtZj-WJSxR-r6j5V-Yyus_2z1s7yI--S7bx_GPAHOveJl1kUTlv3S8ioQhwXFVAbRYFMyGfR=
